class="TruncatedText"><div class="TruncatedText__text TruncatedText__text--5" data-testid="contentContainer"><div><span class="Formatted">I was not expecting to enjoy this book so much. Like many people who live in Rwanda, I think, I have mixed feelings about Dian Fossey, myself leaning on the side of dislike.<br /><br />On the one hand, she almost single-handedly reversed the alarming decline of the world's only mountain gorillas. Unlike lowland gorillas, which are native to a handful of regions of the world and can survive in zoos, mountain gorillas are only found in the Virunga Mountains' volcano chain at the intersection of Rwanda, Democratic Republic of Congo, and Uganda. They cannot survive outside of this specific altitude and vegetation.<br /><br />On the other hand, Fossey is known to have treated her Rwandan staff and local poachers (easily labeled as the "bad guys" but this was also their livelihoods and they more often sought to kill antelopes, with gorillas getting mixed up in the traps) <b>horribly</b>, caring for and respecting the animals more than the humans around her. There is a lot to be said about Westerners imposing themselves in African countries on behalf of conservation, but I'm not well-versed enough to speak to it myself.<br /><br />The former, the positive side of Fossey's legacy, was exceedingly clear through this book. More so than a memoir, it was primarily a non-fiction narrative about the lives of several gorilla families over the course of ten years of observation. I loved learning more about the history of the region and the volcanoes, having hiked 3/8 of them so far, and understanding the family structures of gorillas. It made me want to see them again, but this time in Rwanda (first time was Bwindi Forest in Uganda, March 2019), especially since some of the infant gorillas she describes are now adults and even silverbacks leading their families.<br /><br />I still have mixed feelings about Fossey, but this book has greatly shaped and informed my perspective. At the very end of the book, Fossey rather profoundly states:<br /><br /><i>"American and European concepts of conservation, especially preservation of wildlife, are not relevant to African farmers already living above carrying capacity of their land. Instead, local people need to be educated about the absolutely necessity of maintaining the mountains as a water catchment area. The farmers need to know, not so much about what foreigners think about gorillas, but rather that 10% of all rain that falls on Rwanda is caught by the Virungas and is slowly released to irrigate the crops below. Each farming family's personal survival depends upon the survival of the Parc des Volcans...As a country with much to gain both sociologically and economically from active preservation of land resources, Rwanda could well serve as a monumental example to Zaire and Uganda to gain fuller cooperation in safeguarding the future of the Virungas that all three nations share."</i><br /><br />I like to think Rwanda has done an excellent job over the past 30 years, although it is a shame that gorilla trekking in Rwanda has become a "luxury tourism" activity, with the park permit alone costing $1,500 per person for 1 hour with the gorillas. As I write this, the Ellen Degeneres Campus of the Dian Fossey Fund is being built in Musanze, which includes a well-funded Education Center and the Research Center.<br /><br />Thought-provoking way to end 2020!</span></div></div></div></section></section><section class="ReviewCard__tags"><ul class="CollapsableList"></ul></section><footer class="SocialFooter"><div data-testid="stats" class="SocialFooter__statsContainer"><div class="Button__container"><button type="button" class="Button Button--inline Button--small Button--subdued"><span class="Button__labelItem">6 likes</span></button></div></div><div data-testid="actions"><div class="SocialFooter__action"><div class="Button__container"><button type="button" class="Button Butto