ver the course of ten years of observation. I loved learning more about the history of the region and the volcanoes, having hiked 3/8 of them so far, and understanding the family structures of gorillas. It made me want to see them again, but this time in Rwanda (first time was Bwindi Forest in Uganda, March 2019), especially since some of the infant gorillas she describes are now adults and even silverbacks leading their families.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eI still have mixed feelings about Fossey, but this book has greatly shaped and informed my perspective. At the very end of the book, Fossey rather profoundly states:\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\u003ci\u003e\"American and European concepts of conservation, especially preservation of wildlife, are not relevant to African farmers already living above carrying capacity of their land. Instead, local people need to be educated about the absolutely necessity of maintaining the mountains as a water catchment area. The farmers need to know, not so much about what foreigners think about gorillas, but rather that 10% of all rain that falls on Rwanda is caught by the Virungas and is slowly released to irrigate the crops below. Each farming family's personal survival depends upon the survival of the Parc des Volcans...As a country with much to gain both sociologically and economically from active preservation of land resources, Rwanda could well serve as a monumental example to Zaire and Uganda to gain fuller cooperation in safeguarding the future of the Virungas that all three nations share.\"\u003c/i\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eI like to think Rwanda has done an excellent job over the past 30 years, although it is a shame that gorilla trekking in Rwanda has become a \"luxury tourism\" activity, with the park permit alone costing $1,500 per person for 1 hour with the gorillas. As I write this, the Ellen Degeneres Campus of the Dian Fossey Fund is being built in Musanze, which includes a well-funded Education Center and the Research Center.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eThought-provoking way to end 2020!","rating":4,"shelving":{"__typename":"Shelving","shelf":{"__typename":"Shelf","name":"read","webUrl":"https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/17388876?shelf=read"},"taggings":[],"webUrl":"https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2578988095"},"likeCount":6,"viewerHasLiked":null,"commentCount":0,"viewerCanComment({\"resourceType\":\"review\"})":null},"Contributor:kca://author/amzn1.gr.author.v1.70sF73La7Ulvqp8v5HNYAg":{"id":"kca://author/amzn1.gr.author.v1.70sF73La7Ulvqp8v5HNYAg","__typename":"Contributor","works":{"__typename":"ContributorWorksConnection","totalCount":37}},"User:1336573":{"id":1336573,"__typename":"User","legacyId":1336573,"imageUrlSquare":"https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1442468643i/1336573._UX200_CR0,0,200,200_.jpg","isAuthor":true,"textReviewsCount":4501,"viewableName":"Charles","isBlockedByViewer":false,"webUrl":"https://www.goodreads.com/user/show/1336573-charles","contributor":{"__ref":"Contributor:kca://author/amzn1.gr.author.v1.70sF73La7Ulvqp8v5HNYAg"},"isFollowing":false,"isFriend":false,"followersCount":137},"Review:kca://review:goodreads/amzn1.gr.review:goodreads.v1.aoasV3YDU10VEQLWrPeCVQ":{"id":"kca://review:goodreads/amzn1.gr.review:goodreads.v1.aoasV3YDU10VEQLWrPeCVQ","__typename":"Review","book":{"__ref":"Book:kca://book/amzn1.gr.book.v1.6CPNjLTSGAinB3tto9VFqQ"},"creator":{"__ref":"User:1336573"},"recommendFor":null,"updatedAt":1607053584932,"createdAt":1235969814000,"spoilerStatus":false,"lastRevisionAt":1235969894000,"text":"A lovely book that shows how the love of nature can overwhelm even a trained scientist. Not really a scientific book per se, although there is some good science in the book, especially early on. But a story of passion and a love affair with nature.","rating":5,"shelving":{"__typename":"Shelving","shelf":{"__typename":"Shelf","name":"read","webUrl":"https://www.goodreads.com/review/li